                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114 Mail/9–1944: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-19T19:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 19, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 19—4:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3584. ReDepts 2154, September 8, 1 p.m. A note from the Foreign Office dated
                    September 17 states that the Soviet postal authorities have not received from
                    the Japanese authorities in the Far East any mail from American prisoners of war
                    and interned civilians or mail of any other kind for forwarding via Tehran to
                    the United States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
